Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Existing methods for constrained text generation—such as NeuroLogic Decoding and NeuroStructural Decoding—focus on enforcing constraints at inference time using logic or syntactic rules, primarily through modified decoding algorithms. These approaches excel in handling hard constraints (e.g., must include "dog" as subject) but often treat soft constraints (e.g., preferred tone, style, or semantic coherence) separately or suboptimally, typically via scoring or re-ranking. Moreover, they lack a dynamic orchestration mechanism that balances both types of constraints in a context-sensitive manner without requiring fine-tuning. My key insight is that pre-trained language models (PLMs) already encode rich linguistic and world knowledge, and the challenge lies not in modifying the model architecture or training process, but in *orchestrating* diverse constraint types during generation through a neuro-symbolic interface. This interface should dynamically weigh hard (non-negotiable) and soft (preferred) constraints based on context, generation progress, and constraint interdependencies. Unlike Switch-GPT, which uses attention to switch between lexical constraints in few-shot settings, my idea introduces a hierarchical, interpretable controller that reasons over symbolic constraints while leveraging neural fluency. It also goes beyond NeuroStructural Decoding by integrating not only syntactic but also pragmatic and discourse-level soft constraints (e.g., narrative consistency, emotional arc), enabling high-fidelity generation in complex applications like creative writing or clinical report synthesis—without any task-specific training. The novelty lies in the *dynamic orchestration* framework: a lightweight, plug-and-play module that operates atop any PLM, modulating beam search with real-time constraint prioritization derived from symbolic reasoning and neural compatibility scores.

