  "Idea": "We propose 'Neuro-Symbolic Societies: Multi-Agent Consensus Decoding for Adaptive, Zero-Shot Constrained Text Generation,' a novel framework that reframes constrained text generation as a collaborative decision-making process among specialized neuro-symbolic agents. Each agent encapsulates knowledge about a specific constraint modality—such as Lexical Agent (enforcing keyword inclusion), Syntactic Agent (ensuring grammatical roles), Semantic Agent (validating predicate logic conditions), and Stylistic Agent (modeling tone, register, or narrative voice)—and operates over a shared latent context derived from the base PLM (e.g., LLaMA-2). Instead of a central orchestrator imposing fixed weights, agents independently evaluate candidate continuations using their own symbolic rules and neural plausibility estimators (e.g., BERTScore for style, dependency unification for syntax), producing per-agent compatibility scores. These scores are then fed into a differentiable consensus module—a learnable attention-based negotiation network—that computes a final token distribution by aggregating agent preferences through weighted voting, with weights determined by contextual relevance and historical agreement rates. Crucially, agents can also issue 'constraint proposals' or 'exceptions' based on discourse progression (e.g., the Stylistic Agent may relax formality if the Semantic Agent detects urgency cues), introducing intentional dynamics absent in static frameworks. The negotiation network is trained on a synthetic corpus of multi-agent conflict scenarios (e.g., when including a required medical term breaks fluency), using reinforcement learning with a reward function balancing constraint satisfaction, coherence, and consensus stability. Because all agents rely only on frozen PLM embeddings and symbolic parsers, no backpropagation through the generator is needed, preserving zero-shot transfer. This architecture enables fine-grained, interpretable control over generation while naturally supporting emergent behaviors like graceful degradation, cross-modal compensation (e.g., enhancing clarity when brevity is compromised), and user-intent inference via agent disagreement analysis. Applications span high-stakes domains requiring both precision and adaptability—clinical documentation, legal drafting, educational content—and creative writing tools that evolve with user feedback. By modeling constraint satisfaction as a societal negotiation rather than a top-down directive, this work advances controllable generation toward cognitively plausible, socially inspired AI architectures.",
